                       <h1  style="color:white"><b>Hydroponics Overview</b><h1>

                            <p  style="color:white"><b>Definition:</b>Hydroponics is a method of growing plants without soil, using a nutrient-rich water solution instead. The roots of the plants are directly immersed in the solution, and a combination of light, temperature, and nutrients are carefully controlled to optimize plant growth. This technique is often used in indoor farming, where space is limited, or in areas with poor soil quality. Hydroponics can be used to grow a variety of crops, including vegetables, fruits, and herbs. </p>
						<hr>	
							
                            <h1  style="color:white"><b> About setup of Hydroponics</b></h1>
							<hr>
							<br>
							<center>
							<img src="images/setup.png" align="middle" alt="image not loaded" style="width:900px;height:400px;" >
							</center>
							<p><ol><li>
							
							
							<p>* Choose a hydroponic system: There are different types of hydroponic systems, including Deep Water Culture (DWC), Nutrient Film Technique (NFT), and Drip System. Choose the one that suits your needs, space, and budget.</p>
<br>
<p> * <b>Choose a growing container:</b> The container should be large enough to hold the plant and the water/nutrient solution. You can use plastic containers, buckets, or even PVC pipes depending on your hydroponic system.</p>
<br>
<p>* <b>Choose a growing medium: </b>The growing medium is what holds the plants in place and provides support. Common growing mediums include Rockwool, coco coir, perlite, vermiculite, and clay pellets.</p>
<br>
<p>* <b>Set up the hydroponic system:</b> Install the system according to the manufacturer's instructions. Generally, this involves setting up the container, adding the growing medium, and installing the water pump, tubing, and nutrient solution reservoir.</p>
<br>
<p>* <b>Add the nutrient solution:</b> Mix the nutrient solution according to the manufacturer's instructions and add it to the reservoir. Make sure to maintain the pH level of the solution at the recommended range.</p>
<br>
<p>*<b> Plant the seedlings:</b> Plant the seedlings in the growing medium, making sure that the roots are submerged in the nutrient solution. Place the container in a well-lit area with appropriate temperature and humidity levels.</p>
<br>
<p>* <b>Monitor and maintain: </b>Regularly check the water level and nutrient solution strength, and adjust them as needed. Inspect the plants for signs of pests or diseases, and take necessary action. Prune and harvest the plants when ready.</p>
<br>
These are the basic steps for setting up a hydroponic system. As you gain experience, you can experiment with different hydroponic systems, growing mediums, and nutrient solutions to optimize your plant growth.
							
