</p><hr>
<h1 style="color:white"><b>Growing underground vegetables in Hydroponics</b></h1>
<p >Hydroponics is a type of gardening that involves growing plants in a nutrient-rich water solution, without using soil. Instead, plants are grown in an inert growing medium, such as perlite, coconut coir, or rockwool, which provides support for the plant's roots while allowing water and nutrients to circulate freely.
</p>
<p>Underground plants, like carrots and radishes, can be grown in hydroponics by using techniques that support root growth and development. For example, some growers use net cups or specialized baskets to hold the plants in place and allow their roots to dangle freely in the nutrient solution. Other growers may use a deep water culture (DWC) system, which involves suspending the plant's roots in a nutrient solution that is aerated to promote oxygenation.</p>

<p>there are several types of underground plants that can be grown using hydroponic systems. Some popular options include:
<ol>
<li>1)Carrots</li>
<li>2)Radishes</li>
<li>3)Beets</li>
<li>4)Potatoes</li>
<li>5)Onions</li>
<li>6)Garlic</li>
<li>7)Ginger</li>
<li>8)Turmeric</li>
<li>9)Sweet potatoes</li></ol>
These plants can be grown in a variety of hydroponic setups, such as nutrient film technique (NFT), deep water culture (DWC), or vertical farming systems. However, it's important to note that some underground plants may require more space and specific growing conditions than others, so it's essential to do thorough research before starting a hydroponic garden.</p>
						
                       
